utional history in which groups are older than suggested by fossils and fossil-calibrated molecular clocks. The author discusses possible causes for the endemism of high-level taxa in tropical America and Madagascar, and overlapping clades in South America, Africa, and Asia. The book concludes with a critique of adaptation by selection, founded on biogeography and recent work in genetics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBiogeographyzTropics. 0aBiologyxClassificationxMolecular aspects. 0aVariation (Biology)zTropics. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Evolution.2bisacsh  aafrican ecology.  aafrican species.  aallopatric speciation.  aanimal distribution.  aanimal taxa.  aanimals and geography.  aasian ecology.  aasian species.  abiogeography.  abiological evolution.  abooks for biology majors.  adarwin.  aearth history.  aecology books.  aecology reference.  aendemism.  afossils.  ageographic patterns.  amadagascar ecology.  amammal zoology.  anatural selection.  ascience and evolution.  asouth america ecology.  asouth american species.  atheory of evolution.  atropical america.  atropical species.  azoology books.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052027196840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095180840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520951808423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520951808/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY